The paper deals with information-theoretic limits of support recovery problems, which involve determining a sparse subset of variables relevant in generating observations. This topic is closely related to information theory, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves probabilistic models and statistical analysis, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.SP (Signal Processing) sub-categories. The paper also mentions compressive sensing, which is a technique used in image and signal processing, suggesting that it could belong to the cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the study of trade-offs between error probability and number of measurements, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category.
